{"key":"processedPost-15989451","value":{"id":15989451,"first":15989365,"last":16088616,"when":1332608391,"utime":"03/24/12 07:59 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>a999potts said:</strong><br />What is the easiest way to keep a constant cycle going? <br />I am thinking it would be agar from what i have read so far but i don't know much about it.<br />Once i think i have reached my limit for G2G's, would i just take a piece of fresh mushroom, transfer that to agar and then use that to create a new master grain jar?</blockquote><br />That would not deliver younger cell lines, because the fruit from a 5th <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-to-Grain-Transfers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">grain to grain transfer</a> substrate has a mycelium age of 5 G2G plus the time and cell divisions it took to colonize the bulk substrate and fruit.<br />What you need to do is from spores, <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Strain-Isolation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">isolate strains</a> on <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Agar-Petri-Dishes\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">agar</a>, saving a small sample of each strain in <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Master-Culture-Slants\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">master culture slants</a> in the refrigerator.&nbsp; As you're doing your first grain to grain transfer, start another culture from a master slant to a petri dish.&nbsp; By the time you reach 4 to 5 grain to grain transfers on the original culture, the new one will be ready for the first grain to grain transfer, ensuring you never run out.<br />The above is how I keep supermarkets stocked with a constant supply of fresh product from our <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mountain-Mushroom-Farm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">mushroom farm</a>, all from a single master culture slant.<br />RR"}}